PerformanceLog â€” performance plan
=================================

Owner: PerformanceLog.swift + LogSink.swift
Scope: cut per-emission overhead and add a sampling lever.
Out of scope: call-site reductions (other agents own DirectoryWalk,
Tree.Traverse.Log, LocalStorage caching).


Baseline observations from perf/perf_report.csv + source read
-------------------------------------------------------------
Hot paths emit 5.7M+ lines per session. Per emission today we pay:
  1. NSLock acquire/release for instance-counter dict bump.
  2. ISO8601DateFormatter.string(from:) â€” well-known slow, allocates
     a CFDateFormatter result + Swift String every call.
  3. [(String,String)] array build (copy-on-write, heap), then a
     for-loop with `line += " "; line += k; line += "="; line +=
     format(value:v)` â€” small Strings re-CoW the buffer each "+=".
  4. format(value:) does up to 4 .contains scans + a replacingOccurrences
     allocation, even though the actions log fixed identifiers that
     never contain spaces or quotes.
  5. line.data(using: .utf8) allocates a Data per emission.
  6. corr id: 4 random bytes + 4 String(format:"%02x") allocations +
     .joined() â€” String(format:) is heavy.
  7. sink.write dispatches async â€” that part is fine. Verified
     calling thread does not block on disk I/O for the production
     path (synchronous == false). Tests use synchronous == true and
     queue.sync â€” preserved as-is.


Micro-optimisations
-------------------
M1. Fast wall-clock formatter.
    Replace ISO8601DateFormatter with a hand-rolled fixed-width UTC
    formatter. Cache the YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS prefix per integer second
    of timeIntervalSinceReferenceDate; only the .mmmZ ms suffix is
    rebuilt per call. Output stays ISO8601-with-millis (the docs
    contract). Use UTC (suffix 'Z') â€” the old code used current TZ
    but appended no offset, which was actually a bug; the canonical
    log is now unambiguous UTC. Cache is guarded by the same NSLock
    we already take for the instance counter â€” zero new locks.

M2. Per-action atomic counters via os_unfair_lock-style fast path.
    Keep the existing [String: Int] dict (action names are dynamic
    strings, registering a static enum would force callers to change).
    But shrink the critical section to a single dict bump and rip
    String formatting out of the lock. Already mostly true today â€”
    confirm and keep tight.

M3. Build the line directly into a single String with reserveCapacity.
    Skip the [(String,String)] intermediate. Inline writers append
    "key=value " segments straight to a reusable per-call String with
    a pre-reserved 160-byte capacity (covers the common case in one
    allocation). Values that need quoting take a slow branch; the
    99%-case "fixed identifier" branch does no scans (we know phase,
    action, instance, corr, elapsed_ms never need quoting).

M4. format(value:) only on extra pairs.
    The four/five built-in pairs never contain whitespace/=/quotes.
    Skip the scan for them; only run format(value:) on user-supplied
    extras.

M5. Drop the per-line .data(using:.utf8) allocation.
    Use String.utf8 view via Data(line.utf8) which is a single
    contiguous copy instead of going through the optional-returning
    path. Marginal but free.

M6. Cheaper correlation id.
    Generate one UInt32 with arc4random_buf or SystemRandomNumberGenerator
    .next() and emit 8 lowercase hex chars via a 16-byte LUT loop â€”
    no String(format:), no array map+joined.


New sampling API (additive â€” default off, behaviour preserved)
--------------------------------------------------------------
S1. Public surface:
    PerformanceLog.shared.setSampling(action: String, oneInN: Int)
    PerformanceLog.shared.clearSampling(action: String)
    PerformanceLog.shared.clearAllSampling()

S2. Semantics:
    * One-in-N gates the start/finish PAIR atomically: if we drop
      the start we MUST drop the finish, otherwise unpaired finish
      lines confuse the analyzer.
    * Decision lives in the trace handle (sampled: Bool). A "skipped"
      trace runs no I/O, no format, no signposter calls. Instance
      counter is still bumped â€” we want monotonic ordering even
      across drops, and it's a single int increment.
    * Drop accounting: per-action dropped-pair count. Every 1024
      drops (or on flush()) emit one summary line:
        phase=sampled_summary action=X dropped=N window_ms=M
    * Default oneInN=1 (i.e. all emissions written) for every action.
      Sampling map is empty â†’ behaviour is byte-identical to today.

S3. Thread-safety:
    Sampling map is read on the hot path. Use a struct snapshot via
    NSLock â€” held only for a dict read of one Int. Same lock as
    instance counters (reduces cache lines).


Thread-safety analysis
----------------------
* All shared state (instance counters, sampling map, second-cache for
  the formatter) lives under PerformanceLog.lock. Lock is held only
  for O(1) work â€” no allocs, no I/O. This is strictly less work than
  today (today the lock wraps the counter, today's formatter sits
  outside the lock â€” same pattern preserved).
* PerformanceTrace stays @unchecked Sendable. Its `sampled` flag is
  set at start and never mutated.
* LogSink dispatch model is unchanged. We do not introduce a new queue.


Tests to preserve
-----------------
Currently no PerformanceLog-named test exists, but the contract used
by other tests is:
  * overrideLogFile: URL forces synchronous mode â†’ reads-after-write
    must see the start/finish lines on disk.
  * shared.enabled = false fully suppresses I/O.
  * The line grammar with phase=/action=/instance=/corr= is parsed by
    perf/parse_perf.js â€” keep grammar identical.
  * `flush()` blocks until queued writes land.
All preserved. swift build must pass. swift test must pass for any
file that touches PerformanceLog (currently none direct).


Estimated speedup per emission
------------------------------
Rough back-of-envelope, Apple Silicon:
  * Old: ~3-6 microseconds per emission (ISO8601 ~1-2 us, dict+lock
    ~150 ns, array+string formatting ~1 us, data alloc ~200 ns,
    dispatch enqueue ~200 ns).
  * New: ~700 ns - 1.2 us steady-state (cached prefix â†’ ~30 ns
    formatter; no [(String,String)] array; reserveCapacity single
    alloc; cheaper corr id). 3-5x faster per call.
  * With sampling on a hot action at oneInN=100: 100x fewer disk I/O,
    100x less queue contention. End-to-end SingleDir log volume on
    the worst path goes from millions of lines to tens of thousands
    + one summary line per ~1024 drops.


## Progress notes (finishing agent)

Confirmed in PerformanceLog.swift + LogSink.swift:
  * Public API source-compatible: start, event, finish, measure,
    measureAsync, flush, newCorrelationId all present and same
    signatures as before.
  * Sampling default off: samplingOneInN starts empty; decideSampledLocked
    returns true when the map has no entry for the action or n<=1.
    Behaviour is byte-identical to the pre-sampling logger until a
    caller opts in.
  * PerformanceTrace.skipped: no signposter calls, no I/O, closed=true
    at construction so finish() and deinit are pure no-ops. Instance
    counter is still bumped under the lock so monotonic ordering is
    preserved across drops (matches plan S2).
  * Drop accounting: per-action droppedSinceSummary counter, threshold
    1024 triggers emitSampledSummary, flush() drains pending counts.
  * Critical section in start/event is minimal: counter dict bump +
    sampling map read + (in appendTimestamp) prefix-cache check.
    No string formatting, no Data alloc, no signposter, no disk I/O
    under the lock.
  * Hand-rolled UTC formatter: civil_from_days (Hinnant) algorithm
    is the standard branch-free proleptic-Gregorian conversion.
    Spot-checked: handles month boundaries (Mar 1 / Feb 28-29),
    leap years (400-year era cycle), and post-2001 negative refSeconds
    via the sod < 0 fixup. UTC suffix Z is now correct (old code
    appended Z but used current-timezone Date â€” fixed by going through
    timeIntervalSinceReferenceDate which is UTC-anchored).
  * Tests using overrideLogFile still force synchronous=true in the
    LogSink constructor (PerformanceLog init: `let isTest = overrideLogFile != nil`).
    Production shared singleton stays async.

Tightened by finishing agent:
  * (None) â€” no defects found in the rewrite that required editing.
    The implementation matches the plan as specified.

Sampling wiring:
  * Deferred. The high-volume call sites identified in perf_report.csv
    (DirectoryWalk.SingleDir at 2.85M instances, Tree.Traverse.Log at
    888K instances) are emitted from DirectoryTree.swift /
    DirectoryTreeWalker.swift, which are owned by the DirectoryWalk
    agent. The only other safe startup sites â€” AppState.swift and
    ImageGlassApp.swift â€” are owned by the AppLaunch agent (they
    already touch PerformanceLog for AppLaunch.Total / FirstFrame).
    Per the task constraints, the sampling API is shipped (setSampling,
    clearSampling, clearAllSampling) and the wiring is left to the
    owning agents. Suggested initial call once the DirectoryWalk
    agent's caching lands and they re-measure:
      PerformanceLog.shared.setSampling(
          action: "DirectoryWalk.SingleDir", oneInN: 100)
      PerformanceLog.shared.setSampling(
          action: "Tree.Traverse.Log", oneInN: 100)
    Best site is the early branch of ImageGlassApp.init() right after
    the launchTrace touch, before InitialConfigSeeder is dispatched.

Build verification:
